name: Cocos (Keeling) Islands
background: There are 27 coral islands in the group. Captain William KEELING discovered the islands in 1609, but they remained uninhabited until the 19th century. From the 1820s to 1978, members of the CLUNIE-ROSS family controlled the islands and the copra produced from local coconuts. Annexed by the UK in 1857, the Cocos Islands were transferred to the Australian Government in 1955. The population on the two inhabited islands generally is split between the ethnic Europeans on West Island and the ethnic Malays on Home Island.

geo.Location: Southeastern Asia, group of islands in the Indian Ocean, southwest of Indonesia, about halfway between Australia and Sri Lanka
geo.Area - comparative: about 24 times the size of The Mall in Washington, DC
geo.Climate: tropical with high humidity, moderated by the southeast trade winds for about nine months of the year
geo.Natural hazards: cyclone season is October to April
geo.Environment - current issues: freshwater resources are limited to rainwater accumulations in natural underground reservoirs

government.Dependency status: non-self governing territory of Australia; administered from Canberra by the Department of Regional Australia, Regional Development and Local Government

Capital.time difference:: UTC+6.5 (11.5 hours ahead of Washington, DC during Standard Time)

government.Constitution: Cocos (Keeling) Islands Act of 1955 (23 November 1955) as amended by the Territories Law Reform Act of 1992
government.Legal system: common law based on the Australian model

Executive branch.chief of state:: Queen ELIZABETH II (since 6 February 1952); represented by the Australian governor general
Executive branch.elections:: the monarchy is hereditary; governor general appointed by the monarch on the recommendation of the Australian prime minister; administrator appointed by the governor general of Australia and represents the monarch and Australia

Legislative branch.Legislative branch: unicameral Cocos (Keeling) Islands Shire Council (7 seats)
Legislative branch.elections:: held every two years with half the members standing for election; last held in October 2009 (next to be held in Ocotber 2011)

government.Political pressure groups and leaders: The Cocos Islands Youth Support Centre
government.Flag description: the flag of Australia is used

economy.Economy - overview: Coconuts, grown throughout the islands, are the sole cash crop. Small local gardens and fishing contribute to the food supply, but additional food and most other necessities must be imported from Australia. There is a small tourist industry.

Labor force - by occupation.note:: the Cocos Islands Cooperative Society Ltd. employs construction workers, stevedores, and lighterage workers; tourism employs others

Telephone system.general assessment:: connected within Australia's telecommunication system; a local mobile-cellular network is in operation
Telephone system.international:: country code - 61; telephone, telex, and facsimile communications with Australia and elsewhere via satellite; satellite earth station - 1 (Intelsat) (2001)

commerce.Broadcast media: 1 local radio station staffed by community volunteers; broadcasts of several Australian radio and TV stations are received via satellite (2009)
